{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_hartford_ver01/data/sn92051126/00517174105/1908010801/0080.xml":{"full_text":"THE NEW HAVEN UNION\nU\nWEDNESDAY, JANUARY 8, 1908.\nNotice to Advertisers.\nChange* for advertisements must be in by 10 o\u2019clock In the morning, to\ninsure the change being made the same day.\n-,i E. Katz, Special Advertising Agent, 230 Temple street. New York} 317 U.\n\u25a0I Express building, Chicago.\nIt cannot be guaranteed that obanges left later than 10 o\u2019clock will be\nmade that day.\nBetter attention oan be given to advertisements the changes for which are\nbrought in the afternoon before the day on which they are to appear.\nSAMUEL FESSENDEN.\nfc'\n\u2018i\nThe Hon. Samuel Fessenden, whose death occurred yes\nterday at his home in Stamford, filled a considerable space in\nthe political history of Connecticut for the last quarter of a\ncentury, frequently getting into a commanding place even in the\nnational political road of that period.\nAnd in the judgment of the unbiased mind, it was a credit\njjs\nable position he reached in the shifting and more or less excit\ning events that combined to make the history of the Republican\nparty of Connecticut in the past 25 years. It can be said with\nequal candor that there is no blemish on his fame in the conspicu\nous incidents that brought him into the limelight of national\n;,f Republican politics.\nThe man who was sincere and square with Sam Fessenden\nwould in turn be treated with frankness and fairness. He de\ntested shams and likewise that detestable cleverness which some\ntimes is classified under the heading of tricky, alert statesman\nship. He played the political game in national and state poli\ntics without resorting to subterfuge that was akin to dishonesty\nor crookedness.\nEven if you could not always agree with him in his views\npin state or national policies, he would compel admiration and\nrespgct because of. his candid, open and fearless defense of\nprinciples that he honestly believed in.\nKi\nt v-j.\nBut aside from politics, away from the environments of\nit^te; campaigns and political battles and the ups and downs\nof political life, there was a personal, a friendly, a social side to\n;j Hr.'Fessenden that was as pleasing, as fascinating and as charm\nj ingiy. democratic as one rarely finds nowadays. It was a sort\nOf old-fashioned, homely, true fellowship that gave to him a\npersonality that was as attractive as it was simple and honest.\nIt is the man who has these delightful qualities in his general\nmakeup, whose friendship and interest are genuine and whose\nloyalty requires no prod, that will be missed and sincerely\ny mourned by those who had the good fortune to know him.\nF _ In Mr. Fessenden\u2019s long and successful career as a member\nI pf the Connecticut bar, he was never known to run short in that\nft generosity of heart that invariably marks the kindly disposed\nB prosecutor who forgets not to temper justice with mercy and\nwho has, a desire to lighten the heavy burdens of the unfortunate\nand the erring as far as it is in his power to do so.\nThere is no political foe to Mr. Fessenden in Connecticut\niodtty but will join in the general verdict that he was a believer\n-^.:r.m..a.fair, fearless contest and that he lived right up to that be\nlief. Some of his ambitions perhaps wereinotrealized, and prob\nthe failure of realization may have temporarily impressed\nBut\nJum^ with the idea that republics are not always grateful.\n_ fhal radiant disposition, that good, hearty, honest fellowship and\n5*f c\nbuoyant, courageous determination to see and1 enjoy the sun\nshine\u2122 life, to spread cheerfulness and hope among his fellow\nmen, were sure to soon obliterate all trace of disappointment\nFAd put him back again into the pathway of the philosopher.\nFew who are familiar with Republican politics in Connecti\ncut will need to he told about the high place Mr. Fessenden\nwsftched in the confidence of his party associates and the honors\nthat were very justly awarded to him for the fidelity with which\nlie served his party. He was a splendid type of the American\ncitizen, a true patriot and an unswerving friend.\nM\nr; i\n\nP\ny\nx-\nWOMEN IN CIVICS.\nvf- ./The Women\u2019s Republican clubs of New York have become\n^practically interested in \u201cbeautiful snow.\u201d\nThey, believe that our present method of disposing of it is\nvery' unhygienic. These women are advocating that the snow\nshould be taken from sidewalks and the sides of the streets,\nincluding the gutters, which should be particularly free from\nobstructions, and piled up in the centre of the streets. Thus\nhave one -ridge in the centre of the street and a roadway on\neach side for wagon Or carriage traffic. This would help re\nmove the dampness, as far as possible from the inmates of the\nhouses and the slush from the sidewalk. Then with cleaned\ngutters there would be a free drainage of water and filth to the\nsewers. This, of course, could only be done in residential streets,\nunless the women could induce the car companies to do their\nduty by transporting snow from the streets in return for ad\nvantages they receive from municipalities.\nWe all know how unsatisfactorily snow has been carted\naway; with a ridge at each curb, the melted snow holding the\naccumulated filth, to thaw and freeze alternately until the end\nof winter, when it is carried away; usually only the filth is left.\nThis plan is neither hygienic nor conducive to health. All honor\nto the women who have suggested a better plan. The best plan\nwould be to have it carted away as quickly as possible after it\nfalls, but in the interim keep gutters and catch basins clean.\nThe Mothers\u2019 club of New Haven and the sanitary com\nmitted of the Civic club, are calling the attention of the public to\nlocal unsanitary conditions. The Mothers\u2019 club objects to child\nren being tempted into trying sugar coated pills distributed\non doorsteps where children sample them and they are often\na menace to their health.\nWomen are most interested in the more general use of school\nbuildings, especially as a moral influence. This is one of the\npractical results of the work of the Associated Civic societies.\nThere are distinguished and indefatigable workers among\nthe women in New Haven who are promoting this good work of\nimproving conditions and among these tireless workers might\nbe mentioned Miss Edith Woolsey, Miss Alice Bacon, Mrs. James\nR. Bolton, Mrs. Isham Henderson, Mrs. Hannah Sturges and\nMrs. Leo Herz. Mention should be given, too, to that legion of\nother women in the Woman\u2019s School association who never tire\nju \u00a74vaucing the cause of sanitation and bettering conditions\nlocally.\nCONNECTICUT EDITORS,\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nI'Tom the Hartford Post.\nEncouraging reports continue to\ncome from the industrial centres, con\ncerning the business outlook and the\nsteady return of wholesome conditions.\nIn this state the situation is probably\nnot far different from that obtaining\nelsewhere, and the gratifying reports\nas to Connecticut industries may,\nwithout doubt, be accepted as indicat\ning the average condition of business\ngenerally throughout the country. In\nWaterbury, one of the busiest manu\nfacturing centres in New England,\nheavy orders are being received by\nmany of the large manufactories, near\nly all of which will shortly be running\non practically full time. In New Ha\nven also, business is resuming its pros\nperous volume, and there is a general\nfeeling of encouragement and hopeful\nness in all business circles. In every\nbranch of manufacture, from hard\nware to cotton goods, the outlook is\nthe same, and the optimistic senti\nment is pervading the state, that pros\nperity is coming back, and coming on\nthe run.\nPURITAN SUNDAY.\nFrom the New Britain Herald.\nThe Y. M. C. A., a semi-public in\nstitution, not of course supported by\nany contribution from the city, but an\nInstitution which by reason of its ob\njects has been exempt from taxation\nby a special act of the state legisla\nture; an organization which we are all\npleased to see grow and prosper, could\nbetter fulfill its worthy mission at\nthose times it seems If it opened its\ndoors of a Sunday evening for the ac\ncommodation of its members, and be\nsides for the good example it would\nset other philanthropic enterprises in\nthe city. As matters stand now we\nhave a Pulritan Sunday, with many\nwell meaning people believing that the\nclosing of the regular places of amuse\nment will result in the people flocking\nto church, which is not so by any man\nner of means, and those having the\nopportunity to help those who desire\na proper place to spend a Sunday eve\nning closing their doors against them.\nThat isn't a good policy, it isn't even\na wise one and it seems worthy of\nmore thought and consideration than\nit has thus far received.\nOLD WORLD TITLES.\nFrom the Ansonia Sentinel.\nHow would the Countess of Yar- j\nmouth like to exchange her title, just\nnow, for a little real, sincere, endur\ning love? A swap of this kind would\nheal the heart\u2019s bitterness better than\ncash or castles or social position. Old\nworld titles are not taken very se\nriously on this side of the water, any\nway. Moreover, the average Ameri\ncan man has little use for the woman\nwho possesses little else than a title\nand -who craves for nothing but social\nposition. To his way of thinking, the\nquiet, home-loving, home-seeking wife,\nwith all her multifarious domestic du\nties, her neighborhood relations, her\nfaculty for making her husband hap\npy and for making a good man out\nof the boy, is countess enough and\nqueen enough to satisfy him and make\nhim feel like a king\u2014without acting\nlike one. Her life is filled with tasks\nworth the W'hile. Her name may be\nJones or Smith, but her gentleness,\nher honor and her goodness is her hus\nband's crown.\nTAFT\u2019S DEFENSE.\nProm the Bridgeport Farmer.\nSecretary Taft\u2019s recent address does\nnot seem to have inspired Wall street\nwith any material renewal of confi\ndence in the Federal administration.\nQuite the contrary, in fact, for we find\none of the weekly reviews of the stock\nmarket declaring 1 that \"this fresh\nsuggestion of possible government\ncontinuance of a policy of harrassing\ncorporations is an unpleasant reminder\nof the \"weakest point now existing in\nthe situation\u201d; that \"of the doing3 of\nthe administration no one can be\nsure\u201d; and that \u201cIf infatuation is to\nrule the effect in checking recovery of\nconfidence will be uncertain only in\ndegree.\"\nClearly, Wall street Is pessimistic as\nto the policy of the administration.\nSecretary Taft\u2019s carefully worded de\nfence and endorsement of the Roose\nvelt policy is evidently not considered\nwholly sincere in either direction.\nDoubtless the \u201cstreet\u201d ranks Taft as\ngaining administration aid and influ\nence with one hand, while holding out\nthe other to the big trusts for cam\npaign contributions.\nCREDITABLE RECORD.\nFrom the Bridgeport Standard.\nBridgeport has made a very credit\nable record in the number and value\nof her new buildings during the year\nIS?07, just passed. We have 21 new\nfactories, and it has always been the\nboast of this city since she took rank\namong the big manuacturing towns\nof the country, that her industries\nwere more largely diversified than\nthose of any other city of her size in\nthe union. She is keeping up her repu\ntation along that line and when the\npresent temporary depression has lift\ned all her factories will be once more\nin active operation. It \"has got to\ncome.\"\nLUCKY TRIO.\nFrom the Bridgeport Post.\nHaywood, Pettibone and Moyer\nhave all escaped the death penalty,\nand there is no doubt that they owe\ntheir liberties, if not their lives, to\nthe unbelievable stories told by Harry\nOrchard. A milder story on the part\nof the great confesser might have put\ntheir necks in danger, whether they\nwere guilty or innocent.\nNEW YORK EDITORS.\nTARIFF COMMISSION.\nFrom the New York Tribune.\nSenator Beveridges bill providing for\nthe appointment of a tariff commission\ndeserves serious consideration. Its de\ntails may need to be altered, for it is\nnot clear that a permanent commis\nsion, established as a bureau of the\ndepartment of commerce and labor,\nwould secure as good results as would\na special commission chosen to con\nsider the needs of a particular situa\ntion. A permanent bureau, with five\nmembers at salaries of sr.AOn apiece,\nmight degenerate into a perfunctory!\nhumdrum board of inquiry, duplicating\nthe work of other governmental bu\n-fau.s. It might be better to select a\nNOTKIN SAYS\nTRUSS INSURANCE.\nIs a Great Thing, and We Provide It.\nIt Insures perfect health and comfort, and Is a life-long protection\ntgalnst the grave dangers attending ruptures.\nIf you can't come to us, we will go to you, and It will not cost you\npenny more. Don\u2019t get a truss; get THE truss. We don\u2019t charge for\n\u25a0he services of our expert, because the volume of our business Justifies\nas in the outlay.\nNOTKIN BROS.\nPHARMACISTS.\n24 Church St.\nDive ft 0111 r \u00b0X' The^;tre' als\u00b0 Junction Congress Ave., Washington, La\nois., .>ew Haven, Conn.\nJUST 25 YEARS AGO\nIN NEW Mm\nAND ELSEW.IERi\nThe liman steamer, City of Brussels, from New York for Liver\npool was run down and sunk in the Mersey and eight of the crew and\ntwo passengers were drowned.\nThe number of documents reported to have been issued at the\nPrinti\"3 off'c\u00ae. by authority of the 46th Congress, reach\ned 2.324,264 copies.\nDiamonds worth $50,000 beloonging to Madame Albani, were\nstolen on a train from Philadelphia to New York.\nIn St. John\u2019s hall, the Land Leaue branch held an annual meet\ning and the Rev. Farther Cooney was elected president. .There was\na membership of 65 and a balances of $45 in the treasury.\nA violent earthquake was felt in northern Ohio.\nSan Francisco was complaining of a dearth of small change, es\npecially in dimes and nickles.\nA scheme was reported to organize a company with $250,000,000\ncapital in Columbus, O., in order to purchase all the coal and iron\ninterests of the state. _\nIt was reported that the editor of the Omaha Herald went\nbarefooted.\nIn response to Col. Graham\u2019s orders for the turning over to\nthe state of the uniforms of the Second regiment bard, it was re\nported that everything had been handed in but one hat, three\nbelts ana four pairs of shoulder knots.\nIt was learned that during the panic that followed a slight fire\nor the altar in St. Patrick\u2019s church, this city, a girl aged nine\nyears, had her callar bone fractured. The Rev. Father Fitzpatrick\nwas pastor of St. Patrick\u2019s church.\nSeth Doming died at Wellesley, Mass., aged 94 years and was\none of the oldest Masons in the country, having been a master ma\nson over 70 years.\nCorn rose seven cents a bushel on January options, in\nand the price was 57 1-4 cents.\nChicago\nCharges of irregularities and evil practices on the part of the of\nficers in charge of the construct ion of the new government bundl\ning in Boston had been filed.\ncommission to perform a single pre\nscribed duty and to pick out men for\nthe work of a class not to be greatly\ntempted by an offer of $5,000 a year\nfor a six years\u2019 term of employment.\nBut the general idea of paving the\nway for tariff revision by the creation\nof an investigating commission is\neminently sound. It is probable that\nCongress will undertake to revise the\nDingley schedules at a special session\nbailed in the spring of liki9. The\nchance of an intelligent and equitable\nreadjustment of rates would be greatly\nimproved by a thoroughgoing inquiry\ninto the workings of the old schedules\nand a presentation of the changes\nwhich have taken place in industry\nand commerce in the last decade.\nConditions have greatly altered and\nthe role of the United States as a\nmanufacturing and trading nation is\nvastly different now from what it was\nwhen, the Dingley act was passed in\n1S97. Congress needs information on\nwhich to act, and the country would\nwelcome the report of a competent,\nnon-partisan tariff board.\nFACT FOR THE JURY.\nFrom the New York Press.\nDike the Jenkinses of Williamsburg,\nF. Augustus Heinze, of Montana,\npleads upon his arrest charged with\nillegal banking that his offense is only\ntechnical. The two defenses are also\nalike In the fact that they are made\nnot by the public prosecutor but by\ncounsel for the men accused of crime.\nIn the case of conspicuous and in\nfluential _gentlemen who are believed\nto have broken the state law in New\nTork county this plea was made by\nthe district attorney. By his refusal\nto permit their indictment they are\nspared the necessity of convincing\njuries of their peers of the validity of\ntheir excuse.\nWe guess the method adopted by\nDistrict Attorney Clarke in the Brook\nlyn cases and by the department of\njustice in the matter of the man who\ndid so much to shatter public con\nfidence in our banks is the one that\nthe people approve.\nLIABILITY .DECISION,\nFrom the New York Time3.\nA bad law for a good purpose. That\nis practically the judgment of a major\nity of the justices of the Supreme court\nof the United States as to the national\nlaw fixing the liability of employers en\ngaged in interstate commerce. No one\nwill dispute that the general purpose of\nthe law was good in the sense that it\nwas humane, though there is room for\ndifference of opinion a\u00ab to its efficiency\nand expediency. There was also great\ndifference o\u00a3 opinion among the Jus\ntices themselves on the constitutional\nity of the law and on the reasons why\nit was held by a majority to be uncon\nstitutional. Despite this difference the\nactual decision of th4 court is adverse,\nand the law dies a judicial death.\nAUTO SLAUGHTER.\nFrom the New York Herald.\nAll sorts of penalties have been tried\non the automobile \"scorchers\u201d without\navail, seemingly. They still go rush\ning through the streets, taking an old\ngentleman unawares here or an old\nlady there, picking up and tossing to\ncne side or running over absent mind\ned. Tom, Dick or Harry. Evidently\nthe law doesn\u2019t make \"the punishment\nfit the crime,\" for the gay old game\ngoes on as universally today as it did\nlast year, or the year before, or any\nold time you choose to mention, since\nman made the automobile and the J\ndevil sent the chauffeur.\nCIVIL SERVICE REFORMER.\nFrom the New York Sun.\nMr. Roosevelt\u2019s special message to\nCongress recommending the extension\nof the civil service regulations to some\n1,00 additional employes of the cen\nsus bureau is worthy of an occasional\nbut ardent friend of civil service re\nform. His remarks on \"the nakedness\nof the spoils system\u201d and on political\nappointments breathe an edifying spirit\nwhich reminds us that the principles\nof the late Herman B. Eaton still go\nmarching on.\nDoubtless Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s many vo\ncations and avocations keep him from\nknowing that political activity is the\nchief end of Federal officeholders un\nder the present dispensation; that their\nmain duty and business is to get the\nright sort of delegates to the next Re\npublican national convention; that the\nspoils system has never been so naked\nand unashamed as it is under the en\ni lightened sway of a graduate of the\nUnited States civil service commission.\nThere is no more eager occasional\ncivil service reformer; and when this\ncruel canvass is over we shall listen\nfor more brave words from him on. the\nnakedness of the spoils system.\nSTATE OR NATION?\nFrom the New York World,\nj The indictment of F. Augutus Helnze\nby a Federal grand jury shows that\nthe department of justice means to\nsift the recent banking frauds.\nGreater frauds, committed against\nthe state by men far more dangerous\nand powerful, have been of common\nknowledge In the community for a.\n4.4. .f 4-+4-44-4\nWHEN THE WISE MAN FELL.\nFrom the Chicago Record-Herald.\nHe never bucked the tiger and he never bet a cent\nThat he could find tile cup which held the pea;\nHe never at a circus tried to crawl beneath the tent.\nNor tried to pet a fretful bumble bee.\nHe never bought a gold brick and the never rocked a boat,\nHe never teased a bulldog in his life;\nHe never rushed in madly to lay hold upon the throat\nOf a bully who was pummeling his wife.\nHe never pulled the trigger of an ancient, rusty gun,\nJust to see if it contained a load or not;\nHe never, when the gas leaked, started in upon the run\nWith a lighted lamp to find the leaky spot.\nHe. never signed a paper till he'd read it thru and thru,\nHe never skated where the ice was thin:\nBut they coaxed him into Wall street when the sky was\nsoft and blue,\nAnd they casually stripped him to the skin.\n\n4~*~*-\u00a9~*~* 4 +4-M\nperiod twenty tirAes as long. The\neouty's attorney makes fine promises\non the stump but justice is delayed.\nThe governor does not yet compel the\nenforcement of the iaws of New York.\nBut the national government acts.\nIt is strange that men of all parties,\nin their great need of justice, turn\nmore and more to the policy\u2014danger\nous in excess\u2014of heaping new duties\nupon the central government and arm\ning it with powers until now unprece\ndented?\nOTHER EDITORS.\nNOT OPPOSED TO BRYAN.\nFrom the Buffalo Times.\nInterests which are unfriendly to the\nDemocracy have for some time past\nbeen trying to make it appear that\nMr. Bryan, whose nomination for\npresident at the Denver convention is\na foregone conclusion, is unpopular\nwith the Democrats in the south. In\nproof of the falsity of the assertion\nwe present the following letter from\none of the most distinguished Demo\ncrats in the south to the editor of\nthis paper:\nBirmingham, Ala., Dec. SI, 1907.\nHon. Norman E. Mack, Buffalo, N. Y.\nDear Sir:\u2014Certain newspapers keep on\nsaying that the south has become oppos\ned to Mr. Bryan since his Madison\nSquare Garden speech, which is untrue.\nSince that time, the Democracy of this\nstate, in state convention \u2019assembled,\nhas endorsed Mr. Bryan for president in\n1908. I write you this fact so that you\ncan use it In contradicting these false\nreports. There is nobody opposed to Mr.\nBryan except those who have always\ndone so for the reason that they are\nallied with special interests opposed to\nMr. Bryan's election.\nYours very truly,\nJNO. W. TOMLINSON.\nMr. Tomlinson is one of the ablest\nand most prominent lawyers in the\nsouth. He might have been the suc\ncessor of the late United States Sena\ntor Pettus in the upper house of Con\ngress had he been willing to try for\nthe position. He takes a lively in\nterest in politics, and what he says\nof the sentiment of the people in the\nsouth may be taken as authentic.\nThe newspapers which are fighting I\nMr. Bryan are continually quoting the\nCharleston News and Courier, which\nfor some unknown reason opposes his\nnomination for the presidency, and\ntrying to make their readers believe\nthat its editorial utterances reflect the\nsentiment of the southern Democracy.\nSo far as we know that is the only\npaper in the south that is opposing\nthe nomination of Mr. Bryan.\nIt is plain to observers of the po\nlitical situation that the same Interests\nthat oppose Mr. Roosevelt oppose Mr.\nBryan. Those interests are of the\nspecial privilege class. Those are the\nonly in' rrests that will be opposed to\nMr. Bryan in the campaign of this\nyear.\nLIKE A DARK LANTERN.\nFrom the Rochester Post-Express.\n\u201cWit is like a flash of lightning,\nwhile humor resembles the twinkling\nstar,\u201d observes a Texas paper. But\nmost of the modern variety is like a\ndark lantern with the light shut oft.\nADDED TH0U5AND3.\nFrom the Boston Transcript.\nHad those coal mine disasters oc\ncurred a few weeks earlier they would\nhave addgd at least a couple of thou\nsand more words to the President\u2019s\nmessage,\nCAMPAIGN NOTES,\nBLIND NEW YORK WORLD.\nFrom the Courier-Journal.\nThe New York World is going right\nalong with a campaign for Gov. John\nA. Johnson of Minnesota as the Demo\ncratic nominee for president, just as\nit nothing had happened. If the World\ncould have fallen in with the Courier\nJournal last spring and summer it\nmight now be talking to some purpose.\nIt is too late. Gov. Johnson won\u2019t have\nit. Mr. Bryan won't have it. The\nCourier-Journal exhausted the argu\nment against Mr. Bryan without ef\nfect. In accepting the inevitable it\nsimply takes heart of grace ana makes\na virtue of necessity. The trouble with\nNew York is that it sees nothing in\nthe west and south until after the\nevent, and is too almighty sure of Its\ninsufficiency and ignorance before the\nevent. Our dear Brother Pulitzer has\ngained great riches In the east, but he j\nknew more when he lived in Missouri.\nJOHNSON AND PARKER.\nFrom the Providence Tribune.\nThe New York World is industriously\nbooming Gov. Johnson of Minnesota\nfor the Democratic presidential nomi\nnation on the strength of his having\ncarried that Republican state in 1904\nand 19C6. So far so good; but the\nWorld should remember what hap\npened to Judge Parker, who was\nchosen to lead the Democracy four\nyears ago because he carried New\nYork in 1897. It was urged that what\nhe had done once he could do again,\nbut the event proved the fallacy of\nthis reasoning. Times change and\nmajorities change with them. Gov.\nJohnson could not confidently hope to\ncarry Minnesota as a candidate for\npresident next year unless the good\ntimes of the recent past came abruptly\nto an end and caused so large a meas\nure of discontent as to make probable\nthe success of almost any Democrat\nwho could be named.\nPRESS COMMENTS.\nThe President shook 5,645 hands at\nhis New Year\u2019s reception, not includ\ning those of the Rev. William J. Long,\nHenry M. Whitney, the Hon. William\nE. Chandler, E. H. Harriman and other\ndistinguished members of the Ananias\nelub.\u2014Boston Globe.\nAs if fatally to handicap the Fair\nbanks\u2019 boom, it is now announced that\na professional humorist wants to be\na Fairbanks\u2019 delegate, and that a group\nof abnormally tall persons have or\nganized the Long Men's Fairbanks\u2019\nclub.\u2014New York Post.\nHowever, as long as the magazines\nare willing to pay steen cents a word\nfor hunting and fishing anecdotes, there\nwill be no trouble about our present\nand prospective presidents making a\nliving.\u2014Atlanta Journal.\n\u201cThe press.\" declared the spr -ad\neagle orator, \u201cis the Archimedean lever\nwhich er-which-or\u2014'\n\u201cLifts the lid\" suggested a man in the\ncrowd\ncrowd.\u2014Pittsburg Post.\nThe Assyrian was scratching some\nhien-oglyphic? on a brick.\nSaratoga\nPRUNES\npackced to our order\nin California (Saratoga District)\nwhere the best flavored Prunes\nraised in that State are grown.\nGood size, right color, meaty\nand\u2014above all\u2014full flavored.\nMany people are prejudiced\nagainst California Prunes\u2014and\nrightly so; nothing is much\nmeaner than the \u201ccheap\u201d ones\n\u2014nothing (not even the French\nPrune) much better than the\nbest of them.\nSaratoga Prunes are packed\nin sealed parchment paper car\ntons, full one pound weight\nand, best of all, absolutely clean\nand tree from dirt and dust.\nPackage, 15 cts.\n7 Packages for $1.00\nSiuXGffa&ldnt,\n\u25a038/ Sfr~\n\u2022\u2018What you wmin\u2019?\" asked his chum.\n\u201cHanged If I know,\u201d responded the\nengraver, \u201cbut I guess some of those\nAssyrlologists of the twentieth century\ncan translate it all right.\u201d\u2014Philadel\nphia Public Ledger.\nAn heiress who lived in Dubuque\nWas courted and won by a duque;\nBut the nobleman gay\nMade her wealth fade away.\nAnd she had to go out as a cuque.\n\u2014Philadelphia Press.\nFamily Retainer\u2014Oh, sir, something\nterrible has happened! Your daughter.\nMiss Gwendolyn sir. has eloped with\nthe chauffeur, sir, an\u2019 they\u2019re off In the\nmotor car, sir.\nThe Old Man\u2014Thank the Lord! May\nbe I can save a little money now that\nthe girl and the machine are both\ngone.\nCLIPPINGS.\nOne person In a thousand reaches the\nage of 100 years. ,j\nSpain Is spending $40,000,000 on new\nbattleships and dockyard construction.\nThe old McAuley Water street mis\nsion In New York has started on Its\nthirty-sixth year of work.\nThe Baptists of Virginia in the finan-,\nclal year just ended raised $151,130 for\nmission and relief work.\nAmong the richer classes 343 in 1,000\nlive to sixty years; in the middle class\nes 1T5, of the laboring class 156.\nThe pay of Russian army ofUcers\nhas been increased, but the rank and\nfile will still have to get along with 50\ncents a month.\nThe German minister of war has\nbought the rights of Poulsen\u2019s wireless\ntelephone, which has established com\nmunication successfully between Cop\nenhagen and Berlin.\nThe plan of the proposed Henry Hud\nson memorial bridge at New York calls\nfor a reinforced concrete span of 710\nfeet and represents one of the boldest\nengineering projects of the time.\nThe Salvation army in England In\nthe past year has aided directly or indi\nrectly 20,883 women, 3,162 of them hav\ning been taken into the rescue homes,\nand no fewer than 2,764 have turned\nout well.\n_\nNAIRN INLAID\nLINOLEUM\n\n100 Yd.\nMEASURED, FITTED AND LAID\nFREE\nWHILE THEY LAST.\n\u201cCO,LORS THROUGH TO THE\nBACK.\" CAN BE HAD ON. EASY\nTERMS.\nP. J. KELLY CO.\n817-823 GRAND AVE.\n36-38 CHURCH ST.","height":"25716","width":"20048"}}
